3. Vector
    -> Legacy class. Came in Java 1
    -> When collections came, vector was added in collections.
    -> Behaves as dynamic array and grows as needed.
    -> When array is full, a new array with double size is created and elements from prev array are copied. this can increase overhead.
    -> Main use: Thread Safety in Synchronized env... multithreaded systems.\
    -> Can give capacity. And capacity to increase as well during declaration..
    -> Single threaded env- not recommended as has overhead due to Synchronized.
    -> Multi threaded env - better. but modern implementations have ConcurrentHashMap or CopyOnWriteArrayList
    -> Vectors preferred when thread safety is priority.

4. Stack
  -> Stack = subclass of Vector. Extended by Vector.
    So can have all properties of vector like Stack is synchronized, Dynamic array but constrained by Stack's LIFO structure.
  -> LIFO = Last In First Out structure
  -> Add- push
  -> Last Element - top of stack to removed - pop
  -> To check top element - peek
  -> isEmpty, size,    search at specific index FROM TOP (SEARCH in stack is index from TOP-index)
  -> (IMP) Also, since it is extended by vector, we can also add or remove an element from middle. Yes.
  -> Can use LinkedList as Stack -> addLast, getLast
  -> So stack can be implemented with help of Stack class or LinkedList class
  -> Although internally stack is also an array so we can say we can implement as Array too.






